                                <condition>Not much is known about the condition of the stone, other than that there is some moss at the edge of the stone which may hint that <q>'that part of it must have been not long ago exposed to the air. Such vegetation could not exist on a stone that had been buried for centuries</q> (12). 
                                </condition>
                            </supportDesc>
                            <layoutDesc>
                                <layout>The stone has on one face an <rs type="decoration">incised crown, a bird and the letter N,</rs> with the ogham inscription in a horizontal position. The stem-line is drawn-in horizontally at exactly <dim type="length" unit="feet">1</dim> foot and is as straight as the run of a ruler.
                                </layout>
                            </layoutDesc>
                        </objectDesc>
                        <handDesc>
                            <handNote>The lines have been described by Southesk as scratches though some parts appear to be <rs type="execution"  key="chiselled" ref="https://www.eagle-network.eu/voc/writing/lod/1.html">chiselled</rs>. The fresh whiteness of the lines could indicate that the marks are modern and perhaps fabricated.                         
                            </handNote>
                        </handDesc>
