            <div type="commentary">
                        <p><q>The opening marks appear to consist of a semi-circle below the stem containing three dots - interpretation unclear.</q> with the same mark above the stem slightly overlapping with the first stroke (Forsyth 1996, 504).</p>
                         <p>There is an additional semi-circle above the stem, at the seventh character, containing a dot of which as Forsyth comments any interpertation is unclear (1996, 505).</p>
                         <p>The authenticity of the stone itself is doubtful with subsequent writers condeming it as fabrication. Southesk comments that the text which appears highly improbable shows in the least that the stone has <q>been tampered with in modern times</q> (Southesk 1895, 244).</p>
            </div>
